\section{Methodology}

<<casenuove.setup, echo=F,message=F>>=
library(dplyr)
library(igraph)

load("data/venice-marriages-filtered.rda")
load("data/ducali_dogi_data.rda")

@

This section in organized as follows. In Subsection \ref{ssec:sources}, we describe the different data sources and how they were adapted. In Subsection \ref{ssec:validation}, we discuss how these sources were validated, including a description of potential biases. Subsection \ref{ssec:exploration} presents a descriptive and exploratory analysis is introduced. Finally,  in Subsection \ref{ssec:methods}, we present and justify the methodology we followed to address our research questions.

\subsection{Data sources}\label{ssec:sources}

We rely on three datasets: an existing database of marriages among Venetian nobles; a database of doges elected after 1297; and a third dataset which integrates additional information on noble families drawn from secondary sources. A description of these datasets and of the steps taken to ensure consistency and normalization follows.

%
<<casenuove.marriages,echo=F,message=F>>=
noble_marriages <- read.csv("data/noble-marriages-year.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
first_year <- min(noble_marriages$year)
last_year <- max(noble_marriages$year)
@
%
The first dataset, which forms the basis of our network analysis, consists of  Venetian matrimonial records spanning the period from \Sexpr{first_year} to \Sexpr{last_year}. Originally compiled by \cite{PugaTrefler}, it was normalized and adapted by \cite{merelo2024intra} and \cite{histories4020012}. Records were kept by the Avogaria del Comun, the magistracy responsible for registering marriages involving at least one noble. Most entries are dated and include the spouses’ first names and noble family affiliation. 

<<casenuove.dogi,echo=F,message=F>>=
load("data/ducali_dogi_data.rda")
ducali_dogi_data <- ducali_dogi_data %>% filter( Year <= 1630)
@

The second dataset provides the names of the doges and their years of appointment and is drawn from the {\sf dogesr} package \citep{merelo2022good}.

%
<<casenuove.casate,echo=F,message=F>>=
family_labels <- read.csv("data/family-labels-accession.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
@
%

A third dataset classifies noble families as  \emph{longhi} or \emph{curti}, identifies the \emph{ducali} within the latter, and records the year of their co-optation into the nobility, allowing us to exclude marriages contracted before formal admission. The factional classification follows the division consolidated in the fifteenth century, as discussed in Section~\ref{history}. The dates of co-optation are drawn from \cite{raines2003cooptazione} which reports, for each noble family, both the year of admission and the year of extinction, defined as the last year in which the family appears in the documentary records.
	
%	QUESTO SOTTO E' NELLA LISTA DELLE INFORMAZIONI MA POI SPARISCE NEL DATABASE? DOVE LO METTO? DEVO AGGIUNGERE UN INDICATORE BINARIO DI RICCHEZZA NELLA LISTA SOTTO? 
    
For the sorted list of wealthy families, we have used \cite{chojnacki1973search} who published a rank for the so-called {\em estimo} or census \cite{estimo} taken in 1379. This {\em estimo} was used for fiscal purposes, but for the purpose of this paper we use it as a proxy of the families' economic power at the beginning of the period under study. 

This third dataset is publicly available in the paper's repository under an open licence. For each family, it records:
\begin{itemize}
\item family name;
\item year of admission to the patriciate;
\item classification as \emph{longhi} or \emph{curti};
\item an indicator for \emph{ducali} families.
\end{itemize}

Because the three datasets described are drawn from different sources, we harmonized family names to ensure consistent identification across records. Throughout, we adopt the standardised surnames used by Puga and Trefler. When a direct match was not possible, we proceeded as follows:\begin{itemize}
\item when differences clearly reflected only orthographic variation (e.g., Da Mosto vs Mosto or Mosto, Da), we standardised names to the form used in the Puga and Trefler dataset;

\item when names in the Puga and Trefler dataset did not exactly match those in Raines, we relied on the alternative variants reported by Raines to establish correspondence; for example, the Colleoni/Colleone family appears under Codeglione, with Colleoni/Colleone listed as variants;

\item when Raines distinguished between branches of the same family (e.g., Mora (S. Marcuola) and Mora (S. Felice), we collapsed them into a single family and assigned the earliest admission date, as the matrimonial dataset records only family names. This applies to very few families, all admitted after the period under study, and therefore does not affect the results.
\end{itemize}

We then match the two datasets 
and exclude observations that meet any of the following criteria:\begin{itemize}
\item one of the spouses is not noble (identified in the  Puga and Trefler dataset by an empty “Standard Family Name” field);
\item the marriage predates the admission to the nobility of one of the families involved;
\item the marriage is undated.\end{itemize}
The first two type of records are excluded because they involve a non-noble or a not-yet-noble family and therefore cannot represent political alliances within the patriciate. Undated marriages are excluded because it is not possible to determine the noble status of the spouses at the time of the marriage.  % The file loaded above is already filtered with all these families dropped.



<<casenuove.number_of_matrimonies_per_year, messages=F,echo=F, fig.cap="Number of matrimonies per year", fig.height=4>>=
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
noble_marriages %>% group_by( year ) %>% summarise( matrimonies=n()) -> marriages_by_year
ggplot(marriages_by_year, aes(x=year,y=matrimonies))+geom_line()+geom_point()+theme_minimal()
@

The final dataset contains \Sexpr{length(noble_marriages$year)} marriages. Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.number_of_matrimonies_per_year} reports the number of marriages per year.

\subsection{Validation and biases}\label{ssec:validation}

The main assumption of this study is that the matrimonial network of the Republic of Venice is a good enough representation of the social network and its dynamics for the period under study. We will need to offer some hints on the validity of this social network on its two aspects: nodes and links.

As nodes we are using the {\em casata} or extended family. After the (often called first) Serrata \cite{serrata} in 1297, the number of members of the Maggior Consiglio per family were restricted, so that every family would have only two at most. This preserved, to a certain point, the unity of action by families, so that despite being divided into different {\em rami} or branches (as reflected, for instance, in the aforementioned {\em estimo}), its political and commercial action was often coordinated \cite{chojnacki:1985,romano1987patricians}. Specifically from the point of view of this paper, which is the existence of factions and how this affected the outcomes of the elections, different branches of the family never veered away from the faction they were in.

Considering the number of marriages between two families as edges is justified also by the fact that matrimonies were considered more commercial and political than sentimental affairs Marriage contracts in the Republic of Venice included provisions for how dowries would be paid, as well as shares in commercial enterprises \cite{telek2018three,sperling_1999}. Very often, every nuclear family could marry only one of their daughters due to the amount of dowry that needed to be paid, and that was often limited by sumptuary laws \cite{dowries:chojnacki}. Since effectively families acted together (in an institution called the {\em fraterna}) as commercial enterprises, marriages, used in this study as social links, covered many aspects of the relationship spectrum, validating its use here as a representation of the social network at large.

Once the node and edges chosen for the social network has been validated we need again show the extent in which the sample represented by the matrimonies in the dataset is representative of the whole set of matrimonies that took place in the Republic during the period under study. The dataset was published by Puga and Trefler \cite{PugaTrefler} from a 19th century source picked by Marco Barbaro. Even if we can admit that some samples in the archive may have disappeared along time, the fact is that after the so called Second Serrata \cite{second:serrata}, {\em all} matrimonies involving a noble spouse needed to be registered in the Avogaria di Comun, so in fact the universe of the dataset is supposed to be the whole set of marriages taking place, at least while the Republic of Venice had a functioning bureaucracy.

<<casenuove.marriages.validation, echo=F,message=F, warning=F, fig.cap="Showing the main events in the Republic of Venice over the smoothed chart of marriages per year. Red: Black Plague of 1479; gold: War of the League of Cambrai; green: loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto; brown: war of Candia", fig.height=4>>=
ggplot(marriages_by_year, aes(x=year,y=matrimonies))+geom_line()+
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_segment(x=1479, xend=1479,y=0,yend=80,color="red")+ # Black plague
  geom_segment(x=1510, xend=1510,y=0,yend=80,color="gold")+ # League of Cambrai
  geom_segment(x=1573, xend=1573,y=0,yend=80,color="green")+ # Loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto
  geom_segment(x=1645,xend=1645,y=0,yend=80, color="brown") + # Beginning of the Candia war
  ylim(0,80)+
  theme_minimal()
@

In Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.marriages.validation} we show the smoothed and raw graph of matrimonies per year along with several important events in the history of the Republic\footnote{A more complete analysis of these events, its influence in the social network and corresponding changes of regime in the Republic of Venice is published in \cite{histories4020012}}. After every event with influence in the demography \cite{lane1973venice}, the number of marriages correspondingly declines: the Black Plague of 1479, for instance, shows a number of matrimonies almost always below the trend line (in blue); this occurs again right after the war of the League of Cambrai, which leads to an extended period with marriages below the trend line. The loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto goes even further, designating a complete change of trend, that is accentuated again by the beginning of the 17th century with the war of Candia which eventually led to the loss of Crete and the Republic entering in a terminal decline phase. This, however, falls already outside the period we are interested in.

The main post-hoc validation is the fact that this dataset has been used repeatedly not only by the authors that published it originally, but also by us in \cite{merelo2023self,merelo2024intra,histories4020012}. In general, it is a very good reflection of the social status of different families in the time of the Republic and how they interacted with each other. In particular, \cite{histories4020012} shows how different measures of the matrimonies network reflect the events in the Republic and the different change points that occurred in them.

However, we need to acknowledge the biases present in this dataset, the main one of which is evident in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.number_of_matrimonies_per_year}: a temporal bias. The number of marriages per year does not really start to be significant until approximately 1400; it also decreases dramatically after the end of the Republic, 1797; however, this period is not of interest for the purposes of this paper. What this implies is that whatever conclusion we draw for the initial period covered by the social network will need to take into account that the matrimonies present in the network might not be a sufficient sample of the whole set of matrimonies and thus the social network.

\subsection{Initial exploratory analysis}\label{ssec:exploration}

As initial exploratory analysis, we will show the evolution of the social network for the period under study, that is, the period of the {\em ducali} doges. We will use a moving window of 75 years, which is supposed to include "living memory" of past social ties \cite{social:memory}, repeated every 25 years.

<<casenuove.graphs,echo=F,message=F,fig.cap="Sequence of marriage graphs for the period under study, from 1350 every 50 years, spanning 75 years. We highlight here the vecchie (gold), the ducali families (red), as well as the families one of whose members was elected as doge during the period.", out.width="50%", fig.show="hold">>=
DEPTH_IN_YEARS <- 75

lunghi <- family_labels[ family_labels$Group == "Lunghi", ]$Family
ducali <- family_labels[ family_labels$Ducale == 1,]$Family
quaranta_famiglie <- c(lunghi,ducali)

quaranta_famiglie <- quaranta_famiglie[ !(quaranta_famiglie %in% c("Steno", "Da Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

window_sequence <- seq(from = 1350, to = 1600, by = 50)
assortativity <- data.frame( curti_lunghi = numeric(),
                             ducali = numeric(),
                             in_quaranta = numeric(),
                             distance_curti_lunghi = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_corti = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_lunghi = numeric(),
                             intra_lunghi = numeric(),
                             intra_ducali = numeric(),
                             intra_corti = numeric(),
                             intra_quaranta = numeric(),
                             intra_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             quaranta_e_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             year = integer() )

load("data/doges.years.rda")

for (y in window_sequence ) {

  marriages_window <- noble_marriages %>%
    filter(year <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )
  
  doges <- unique(doges.years[ doges.years$Start >= y & doges.years$Start <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS, ]$Family.doge)
  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")
  
  V(marriage_graph)$Faction <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% lunghi, "Lunghi", "Corti")
  V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_lunghi <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Faction == "Lunghi", 1,2)
  assortativity_curti_lunghi <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_lunghi, directed = FALSE)
  
  V(marriage_graph)$Ducale <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Ducale == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_ducali <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali, directed = FALSE)
  
  V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% quaranta_famiglie, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_quaranta <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta, directed = FALSE)
  
  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight
  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% lunghi, "Lunghi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, "Ducali", "Corti"))
  V(marriage_graph)$color <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Lunghi",
                                    "gold", 
                                    ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group=="Ducali","red","white"))
  
  V(marriage_graph)$shape <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% doges, "square", "circle")
  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])
  plot(marriage_graph_main,
        vertex.size = 5,
        vertex.label = NA,
       vertex.color = V(marriage_graph)$color,
        edge.width = E(marriage_graph)$weight,
        layout = layout_with_kk,
        main = paste("Marriage Network from", y, "to", y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS)
  )
  
}
@

These graphs, shown in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.graphs} give an overview of the evolution of the social network during the period of interest, already reveal some patterns. Although they represent the main connected component of the network slices, they gather most families and all the doges, shown here as squares. While in the first two charts (for 1348 and 1373) there are some {\em lunghi} doges (red squares), most doges from them on are "red" right until the end of the period, when some "gold" are again seen. From 1448 (after the Foscari doge was forced to resign) until the 1548-1623 period, when Bembo was elected as a doge, there are only "red" squares, that is, {\em ducali}.

We can also observe the position of these families with doge among the network, which is, qualitatively speaking, not very central, not even within its own faction. In the 1523 to 1598, for instances, the families that got a doge elected are clearly in the periphery of the network.

Another interesting thing to observe is the lack of clear factionalization. In no period is a clear pattern of connection within the {\em ducali} or {\em lunghi} family that excludes each other, and the rest of the families. Although the periphery is almost always "white", i. e., non {\em ducali} {\em curti} families, there is no clear pattern of occupation of the most central positions in the graph by any of the two "colored" factions, and certainly not by the families that manage to get a doge elected. On first sight another observation that can be made is that network patterns are very similar, with all families being closely connected, except in the first and last graph. In the former it must be probably due to the bias in the dataset that has less marriages in that period; however, the latter might be a reflection of the change that took place during that period, when the {\em ducali} period ended and {\em lunghi} family back again started to monopolize the doge job. 

The last graph, in fact, reflects a period of transition where there are two {\em ducali} doges of the families Donato and Priuli, three {\em corti} of the families Valier, Pesaro and Erizzo, and 4 {\em lunghi}: Bembo, Corner, Contarini and Memmo.

From this initial exploratory analysis we can draw several conclusions: first, that the position of doge is {\em not} taken by the family with the highest social status. Second there is not a clear division between so-called {\em factions}: all families have ties with each other, and most of them are indeed connected one way or another. We need then to see whether there is another angle of analysis that can explain the monopolization of the doges by a faction, the {\em ducali}, during a 200-year period.

\subsection{Searching for factions in social networks} \label{ssec:methods}


